<subSubSection id="2A526DB8DAF59434386838BEE397F7DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph id="95F21C8CD75E79367591C12042012E76" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CEC094E44670BC1822B465A876F83048" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Animal of small size, up to 12 mm in examined specimens, elongate oval, moderately elevated, color of tegmentum tan or creamy white. Head valve semicircular, sculpture with about nine equally spaced, nodulose, annulate and well defined radial ribs. Intermediate valves rectangular, lateral areas well defined, sculptured with two strong radial ribs. Central area with about eight longitudinal riblets per side, well-marked in the pleural areas but becoming obsolete at the jugum. The riblets tend to converge anteriorly and are not latticed. Posterior valve semi-oval, elevated at the central mucro, with nine well defined radial ribs. Girdle yellowish white, dorsally covered with small scales (After 
<bibRefCitation id="FDE66BA1C5EA46879FCCC127A917BFE9" author="Ferreira, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="56 - 64" title="The genus Calloplax Thiele, 1909 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) in the Americas." volume="77" year="1978">Ferreira 1978</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FDDB1F3CC9ADED7F49CAFBF98130E3DA" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="material examined">
<paragraph id="3EB1D575F3B20F9DBB7E88D7CE780CA9" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Material examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9CD9128791B1B2495B74F9C0D2EE4063" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Specimens found under rocks in a tidal pool at Obispito (MPCCL 3072014B, 1 specimen), Sur de Playa Ramada and under rock slabs sunken under boulders in Peninsula Calderilla (SBMNH 452241, 1 specimen).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AF5AF6FD157F7AB05BC419F1ACED485A" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="527CD1149D1E1F9C90DAB9F192F71E40" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="73E70EB4DF7D3110C42EDAB5D6B81596" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<bibRefCitation id="653ADCF812F852C667EF24D6E4317E6E" author="Plate, LH" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Jahrbuecher, Abteilung fuer Systematik, Oekologie und Geographie der Tiere" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="15 - 216" title="Die Anatomie und Phylogenie der Chitonen. Fauna Chilensis 2 (1)." volume="2" year="1899">Plate (1899)</bibRefCitation>
described this species for Isla Pacharos (=
<normalizedToken id="96BBD9C29592433561382AE3992BF04E" originalValue="Pájaros">Pajaros</normalizedToken>
), near Coquimbo, Chile (
<geoCoordinate id="9B8EFA56617E9CBBC409EFF580D4623C" direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-29.966667">29°58'S</geoCoordinate>
; 
<geoCoordinate id="20323793BB02657136B8809FEE365591" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-71.35">71°21'W</geoCoordinate>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="F66DC044C677631359D6A59058A91DA9" author="Ferreira, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="56 - 64" title="The genus Calloplax Thiele, 1909 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) in the Americas." volume="77" year="1978">Ferreira (1978)</bibRefCitation>
additionally recorded this species from the intertidal of Pozo Toyo, South of Iquique, 
<normalizedToken id="21CF588596A374220FE2B3F1B482C082" originalValue="Tarapacá">Tarapaca</normalizedToken>
Province (
<geoCoordinate id="C3C72060949B548B6BD4420F0A117F20" direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-20.416666">20°25'S</geoCoordinate>
; 
<geoCoordinate id="F91D00D581FEFA9038828964228F8739" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="92" value="-70.175">70°10.5'W</geoCoordinate>
) and mainland East of Isla Santa 
<normalizedToken id="740A09C71F978659BFEB7929A4ECCFF6" originalValue="María">Maria</normalizedToken>
, North of Antofagasta, Antofagasta Province (
<geoCoordinate id="B5AD9E1E59EA68BFE9A67E0FC9222D92" direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-23.416666">23°25'S</geoCoordinate>
; 
<geoCoordinate id="EA443C340FF180FB4C2609B65B88BBFA" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-70.6">70°36'W</geoCoordinate>
) from specimens housed at the LACM. A specimen labelled 
<taxonomicName id="693BBDDF90F3D0D6D9DB3E4D81503892" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chiton janeirensis" order="Chitonida" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="janeirensis">Chiton janeirensis</taxonomicName>
(NHMUK 197742) identified by 
<bibRefCitation id="C7C06BDD6539F48AE692335F9D6A322E" author="Ferreira, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="56 - 64" title="The genus Calloplax Thiele, 1909 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) in the Americas." volume="77" year="1978">Ferreira (1978)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName id="90149D1850CC6B022DD879618C99F0EA" class="Polyplacophora" family="Callistoplacidae" genus="Calloplax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Calloplax viviparus" order="Chitonida" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="viviparus">Calloplax viviparus</taxonomicName>
extended the southern distribution of this species at Valparaiso (
<geoCoordinate id="B41AD335D9F95A91881ED6341B08D466" direction="south" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="-33.033333">33°02'S</geoCoordinate>
; 
<geoCoordinate id="4B65814BF67098C4740A06ADC6DE1753" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-71.63333">71°38'W</geoCoordinate>
). This is the first time this species is recorded, in the field, since its description and the present record fills a gap in the distribution in Chile of this rare species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CEFB3E01F724ABDD0B77371A30F18979" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="D6064118EDC4452781CE7198D56D68B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5692F318526DEDEF5224CE6C8832078" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
This is a rare species, found in only two of the locations under study; in both places this species was found under rocks sunken in tidal pools, associated to encrusting sponges and to communities of the small mussel 
<taxonomicName id="B20406CE3BDE8008150A1428083A9128" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Brachidontes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brachidontes granulata" order="Mytilida" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="granulata">Brachidontes granulata</taxonomicName>
(Hanley, 1843). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="C8AB4340A7F4162DEDED953F5D35BF1C" author="Plate, LH" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Jahrbuecher, Abteilung fuer Systematik, Oekologie und Geographie der Tiere" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="15 - 216" title="Die Anatomie und Phylogenie der Chitonen. Fauna Chilensis 2 (1)." volume="2" year="1899">Plate (1899)</bibRefCitation>
this species is ovoviviparous; that cited author found about 15 embryos, some with seven shell valves, in the ovary of a single specimen. In fact, this is the only chiton species ever reported to be ovoviviparous (
<bibRefCitation id="DFD80DA7E87911D0BB6984AD4F05D204" author="Pearse, JS" editor="Giese," journalOrPublisher="Academic Press, New York" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="27 - 85" title="Polyplacophora." volumeTitle="Reproduction of marine Invertebrates" year="1979">Pearse 1979</bibRefCitation>
). This species is somewhat similar to 
<taxonomicName id="77FF3D045CF63C94D8437FB3962E3BED" class="Polyplacophora" family="Callistoplacidae" genus="Callistochiton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callistochiton pulchellus" order="Chitonida" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pulchellus">Callistochiton pulchellus</taxonomicName>
(Gray, 1828), differing in the coarse sculpture (especially in the anterior valve, with fewer and stronger ribs), the presence of longitudinal riblets in the central areas, and the more yellowish body color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
